            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this cam design calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool designs a radial (disk) cam with a translating, inline
                follower. You specify the base circle radius, required lift, and
                the angular spans for rise, dwell, and return. The calculator
                then applies the selected motion law to generate:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Follower displacement \( s(\theta) \)</li>
                <li>Velocity \( v(\theta) = \frac{ds}{dt} \)</li>
                <li>Acceleration \( a(\theta) = \frac{d^2 s}{dt^2} \)</li>
                <li>
                  Jerk \( j(\theta) = \frac{d^3 s}{dt^3} \) (internally, for
                  smoothness checks)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The cam surface radius at each angle is \( r(\theta) = R_b +
                s(\theta) \), where \( R_b \) is the base circle radius. The x–y
                coordinates are then:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code>
                  x = r(\theta) \cos\theta, &nbsp; y = r(\theta) \sin\theta
                </code>
              </div>

              <h3>Supported motion laws</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Constant velocity (CV)</strong> – linear displacement
                  vs. angle, with step changes in acceleration at the ends.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Simple harmonic motion (SHM)</strong> – sinusoidal
                  motion with continuous velocity and acceleration, lower jerk
                  than CV.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>3–4–5 polynomial</strong> – a 5th-order polynomial
                  with zero velocity and acceleration at both ends; very smooth
                  and widely used in high-speed cams.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Formulas used</h3>
              <p>
                Let \( \theta \) be the cam angle in radians during the rise,
                and \( \beta \) the rise angle span in radians. Define the
                normalized angle \( u = \theta / \beta \), \( 0 \le u \le 1 \),
                and lift \( h \).
              </p>

              <h4>1. Constant velocity rise</h4>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\( s(u) = h u \)</p>
                <p>\( v(u) = \dfrac{ds}{dt} = \dfrac{h}{\beta} \omega \)</p>
                <p>\( a(u) = 0 \)</p>
                <p>
                  where \( \omega = 2\pi n / 60 \) is cam speed in rad/s for n
                  rpm.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h4>2. Simple harmonic motion (SHM) rise</h4>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\( s(u) = \dfrac{h}{2} \left(1 - \cos(\pi u)\right) \)</p>
                <p>\( v(u) = \dfrac{h \pi}{2\beta} \sin(\pi u)\, \omega \)</p>
                <p>
                  \( a(u) = \dfrac{h \pi^2}{2\beta^2} \cos(\pi u)\, \omega^2 \)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h4>3. 3–4–5 polynomial rise</h4>
              <p>The normalized displacement is:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\( s(u) = h \left(10u^3 - 15u^4 + 6u^5\right) \)</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                which satisfies \( s(0)=0, s(1)=h \) and zero velocity and
                acceleration at both ends.
              </p>

              <h3>Interpreting the plots</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Displacement plot</strong> shows how far the follower
                  moves vs. cam angle.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Velocity and acceleration plot</strong> helps you
                  check for peaks that may cause high contact forces or
                  vibration.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Cam profile plot</strong> is the actual cam shape in
                  Cartesian coordinates, ready to export to CAD.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Design tips</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Use SHM or 3–4–5 for high-speed cams to reduce shock and
                  noise.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Increase rise/return angle spans or reduce rpm if acceleration
                  peaks are too high.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Ensure the minimum radius (base circle) is large enough to
                  avoid undercutting and maintain a reasonable pressure angle.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <!-- FAQ -->
